ğŸ’¥ Hints / Gotchas / Exam Tips
This is often paired with cron job abuse â€” if a root cron job runs a script you can modify or that calls ls, cp, etc., hijack the command.

Writable folders in PATH = instant attack surface â€” especially if owned by your current user.

Always check what directory you're in when trying this. The . trick only works if you're in the same folder as the fake command.

Tools like sudo, su, ssh, and scp are often NOT vulnerable here because they use absolute paths â€” focus on scripts written by humans, not system tools.

Try it with harmless payloads first, like echo "GOTCHA" â€” then escalate to reverse shell if it works.

If a binary executes without full path AND the script has SUID or runs as root via cron â€” this is a root escalation vector.

Donâ€™t forget to clean up after this trick in labs or live environments â€” dropped fake binaries can linger.


ğŸ’¡ If You Have Write Access in $PATH (or Can Modify $PATH):
âœ… Yes, you can absolutely abuse it by:
Dropping a malicious binary into a writeable directory already in $PATH or

Modifying the $PATH to point to a directory you control (like . or /tmp/fakebin) and placing a malicious script in it

ğŸ”“ What Kind of Malicious Binary?
Depends on what the victim process calls, and who runs it.

ğŸ§¨ Scenario 1: Cron Job / Script / SUID Binary is Running ls (or cat, tar, etc.)
â¡ï¸ Replace it with your fake binary that does one of the following:

ğŸª Option A: Spawn a root shell
If you're abusing a SUID binary or cron job:

bash
Copy
Edit
echo -e '#!/bin/bash\n/bin/bash -p' > ls
chmod +x ls
-p preserves privileges. If run as root, youâ€™ll drop into root shell.

ğŸ•³ï¸ Option B: Reverse shell
bash
Copy
Edit
