chmod +x ls
ğŸ” Option C: Dump shadow file
bash
Copy
Edit
echo 'cat /etc/shadow > /tmp/shadowdump' > ls
chmod +x ls
ğŸ§  How GTFObins Fits In:
GTFObins shows known-good binaries that are either:

SUID-safe (run with elevated perms)

Abusable via $PATH manipulation

Able to escalate, bypass restrictions, or exfiltrate

So if a script or privileged job runs tar, awk, perl, env, cp, etc., you go to GTFObins and use the PATH-based method listed for that binary.

Example: Letâ€™s say the target script runs env
â¡ï¸ Go to: https://gtfobins.github.io/gtfobins/env/

Use the "Sudo" or "Shell" technique (depending who runs it)

bash
Copy
Edit
echo -e '#!/bin/bash\nbash -p' > env
chmod +x env
Boom â€” if that script is executed by root, and your env gets called first, youâ€™re in.

ğŸ“Œ CPTS / Exam Mindset:
Think This	Do This
â€œCan I write to a folder in $PATH?â€	Drop malicious ls, cp, or any binary thatâ€™s used
â€œCan I modify $PATH?â€	Prepend . or your controlled dir and drop fake binaries
â€œThis script doesnâ€™t use full pathsâ€	Abuse $PATH and hijack the weak command
â€œThis job runs every minuteâ€	Drop payload and wait for it to fire
â€œThis binary is in GTFObinsâ€	Use their exact payload + test in your environment
